    .slide#about
      .card
        .subsection#subsection-titleblock
          figure
            img(src="./assets/img/sketch.png", alt="")
          .subsection#subsection-titleblocktext  
            h2.desc The Robots in Groups (RIG) lab explores social and technical issues surrounding the placement of robots within groups and teams.

              
        .subsection#subsection-threeblock
          h2.subsection-title How do robots shape the dynamics of work groups and teams in existing settings?
              .subsection#subsection-threeblockone
                p It is not clear how robots affect core group processes such as conflict, emotion regulation or power dynamics, and how the impact of a robot on these processes shapes short and long-term group outcomes. One of our key research questions is to better understand how robots affect these processes and outcomes, which is increasingly pressing as several companies have announced autonomous robots for group settings. 


            
        .subsection#subsection-threeblock
          h2.subsection-title How does a robot’s behavior shape how humans interact with each other in dyads and in larger groups and teams?
            .subsection#subsection-threeblocktwo
              p Little is known about how robots impact the ways in which people interact with each other and even less is known about how robots impact or should impact the way people interact with each other in more complex group settings. To investigate this question we perform behavioral studies that examine how a robot’s behavior shapes human-human interactions in dyads, teams and larger groups.

                
            
        .subsection#subsection-threeblock
          h2.subsection-title How can robots improve the performance of work groups and teams by acting on social processes?
            .subsection#subsection-threeblockthree
              p Given that the social and emotional functioning of groups and teams has been shown to be crucial for group performance, we see an opportunity for robot to improve group performance by acting on teamwork processes that ensure the social functioning of teams. We use iterative design approaches to develop robots that employ social behaviors to improve team performance.


            

    .slide#about
      .card
        .subsection#subsection-about-us
          h2.subsection-title About Us
          .subsection-content
            figure
              img(src="./assets/img/gates.png", alt="")
              figcaption The Robots in Groups (RIG) lab explores social and technical issues surrounding the placement of robots within groups and teams..

            p We conduct research through design, behavioral science approaches, and field observations. Our work seeks to contribute to our basic understanding of group dynamics and how group dynamics can be shaped by robots implicitly and by design.
              | . Of our research is conducted within the 
              a(href='http://infosci.cornell.edu/', target='_blank') Information Science Department on Cornell's Ithaca campus.
              | . If you are interested in working with us, please get in touch below.

          .subsection#subsection-news
            h2.subsection-title News
            .subsection-content
              ul#news-list: each n in news
                li.news
                  .project-info
                    p
                      span.fa.fa-newspaper-o
                      span= n.date
                      span.news-title!= n.title

        .subsection#subsection-people
          h2.subsection-title People
          .subsection-content
            ul#people-list: each p in people
              li.person
                img(src='#{p.image}')
                .person-info
                  a(href=p.link, target='_blank')
                    h3.person-name= p.name
                  p.person-title= p.title
                .person-contact
                  a.person-email(href='mailto:#{p.email}')= p.email
                  if p.twitter
                    a.person-twitter(href='https://twitter.com/#{p.twitter}') @#{p.twitter}
        

  
        

    .slide#publications
      .card#publications-card
        h2.subsection-title Publications
        ul: each p, idx in publications
          #mobile
            li
              .image(style='background-image: url(#{p.image})')
              p= p.mobileInfo
              .links
                each l in p.links
                  a(href=l[1], target='_blank')
                    span= l[0]
                    if l[2]
                      span.fa(class='fa-'+l[2])
                  p 
          #desktop
            li
              .column#image
                if !p.video
                  img(src=p.image)
                else
                  a(class='venobox_custom', data-type='inline', href='#'+'pub-video-'+idx)
                    .pub-video-overlay
                      span.fa.fa-play-circle
                  img(src=p.image)
                  div.pub-video(id='pub-video-'+idx)
                    video(width='800', height='600', controls='')
                      source(src=p.video, type='video/mp4')
                      | Your browser does not support the video tag.
              .column.pub-info
                p#title
                  if p.isAward
                    span.fa.fa-trophy
                  span= p.title
                p#author= p.author
                p#conference
                  span= p.conference
                  span= '  [' + p.type + ']'
                if p.isAward
                  p#isAward= p.isAward
                .links
                  each l in p.links
                    a(href=l[1], target='_blank')
                      span= l[0]
                      if l[2]
                        span.fa(class='fa-'+l[2])
              .column#abstract
                p= p.abstract 
        .pub-overlay
          span.fa.fa-chevron-down

